Learning objectives

  • Describe the structure and function of the lymphatic system
  • Understand the processes involved in innate immunity
  • Explain adaptive immunity including both cellular and humoral mechanisms
  • Suggested reading
    • Saladin, Anatomy & Physiology: The Unity of Form and Function 9e
      • 21.1-21.5

The Lymphatic System

  • Functions include
    • Fluid recovery
      • Capillaries only reabsorb 85%, the rest is reabsorbed and returnby the lymphatic system
    • Immunity
      • Immune cells in the lymph nodes guard against foreign matter
    • Lipid absorption
      • Lacteals absorb dietary lipids (not absorbed by blood capillaries)
  • Components of the lymphatic system
    • Lymph (clear fluid)
    • Lymphatic vessels
    • Lymphatic tissue
      • Aggregates of lymphocytes and macrophages
    • Lymphatic organs
      • Lymph nodes, spleen, thymus, tonsils and red bone marrow

Figure 21.1

Lymphatic vessels

  • Lymphatic capillaries consist of a sac of thin endothelial cells
    • Large gaps allow bacteria/lymphocytes/etcto enter
      • Not joined by tight junctions and basal lamina isdiscontinuous
    • Overlapping edges act as a valve that open under high pressure
  • Flow through lymph vessels is similar to venous return
    • Rhythmic contractions of lymph vessels
    • Valves prevent back flow
    • Pressure generated from skeletalmuscles and arterial pulsations

Figure 21.4

Figure 21.2

Lymphatic cells

  • Macrophages
    • Large phagocytic cells of the connectivetissues
    • Also present antigenic fragments to certain Tcells
  • Dendritic cells
    • Mobile antigen presenting cells found inepidermis, mucous membranes andlymphatic organs
  • Reticular cells
    • Stationary antigen presenting cells part of theconnective tissue in lymphatic organs
  • Neutrophils
    • Anti-bacterial leukocytes
  • Natural killer (NK) cells
    • Large lymphocytes that attack bacteria,transplanted tissue and host cells that areinfected viruses or cancerous
  • T lymphocytes (T cells)
    • Thymus dependent lymphocytes (mature inthe thymus)
  • B lymphocytes (B cells)
    • Lymphocytes that differentiate into plasmacells (which secrete antibodies)
    • Mature in bone marrow

Lymphatic organs: Red bone marrow

  • Red bone marrow produces lymphocytes for the immune system
    • In addition to producing all elements of blood
  • Sinusoids within the marrow are lined with reticular cells
  • Reticular cells secret factors that cause stem cells to develop into leukocytes (WBC), erythrocytes (RBC)and megakaryocytes (platelet making cells)

Lymphatic organs: Thymus

  • Thymus develops lymphocytes and secretes hormonesthat regulate their activity
  • Cortical epithelial cells form a blood-thymus barrier
    • Prevents developing lymphocytes from contactingantigens
  • Medullary epithelial cells form thymic corpuscles
    • T cells spend last 3 weeks developing in thymiccorpuscles before entering blood of lymphatic vessels

Figure 21.9

Lymphatic organs: Lymph Nodes

  • Lymph nodes have two functions:
    • Site of T and B cell activation
    • Cleanlymph
  • Approximately 450 lymph nodes in an adult
    • Cervical lymph nodes
    • Axillary lymph nodes
    • Thoracic lymph nodes
    • Abdominal lymph nodes
    • Intestinal and mesenteric lymph nodes
    • Inguinal and popliteal lymph nodes
  • Lymph nodes may become swollen and painfulto touch when challenge by an antigen

Figure 21.10

Lymphatic organs: Tonsils

  • Tonsils protect against ingested andinhaled pathogens
  • Tonsillar crypts are lined by lymphaticnodules
    • Also, often contain food debris,bacteria and antigenic chemical

Figure 21.12

Lymphatic organs: Spleen

  • The spleen contains two types of tissue
    • Red pulp (erythrocytes)
    • White pulp (lymphocytes and macrophages)
  • Highly permeable capillaries allow RBCs to leave andre-entertheblood stream
    • Old RBCs will rupture
      • Macrophages will phagocytise their remains
  • Lymphocytes and macrophages monitor blood for antigens
  • Angiotensin II will stimulate the spleen to release large numbersof WBCs into the blood
    • Import for microbial infection, large wounds

Figure 21.13

Immune system

  • The immune system is a collective term for numerous defensive cells and mechanisms
  • Often separated into:
    • Innate immunity
      • Epithelial barriers such as skin and mucous membranes
      • Phagocytes/proteins/fever
      • It is local, nonspecific and lacks memory
    • Adaptive immunity
      • A group of mechanisms produce a memory of the pathogen allowing a quicker response in thefuture

Leukocytes

  • Neutrophils
    • Mainly located in connective tissue
    • Phagocytosis and digestion
    • Lysosomes migrate to cell surface and degranulate, hereby releasing enzymes into the tissue whichcreate oxidizing agents
  • Eosinophils
    • Mainly located in mucous membranes
    • Phagocytosis, produce oxidizing agents and neurotoxins, promote basophils and mast cells, limithistamine
  • Basophils
    • Secrete chemicals to activate other leukocytes (leukotrienes, histamine and heparin)
  • Lymphocytes
    • Already covered nature killer cells, T cells and B cells
  • Monocytes
    • Move from blood to connective tissues and transform into macrophages

Antimicrobial proteins

  • Interferons
    • Released when leukocytes become infected with viruses
    • Causes neighbouring cells to produce antiviral proteins and activate NK and macrophages
  • Complement system
    • A group of 30 or more globulins synthesized by the liver
    • Circulate in the blood in an inactive form
    • Activation by pathogens leads to inflammation, immune clearance, phagocytosis and cytolysis

Fever and inflammation

  • Fever is an elevation of body temperature
    • Pyrogens stimulate anterior hypothalamus
    • Elevated temperature
      • Enhances the actions interferons and antimicrobial proteins
      • Inhibits bacteria reproduction
  • Inflammation is characterised by local redness, swelling, heat and pain
    • Limits the spread of pathogens
    • Removes debris of damaged tissue
    • Initiates tissue repair

Adaptive immunity

  • Cellular (cell-mediated) immunity
    • Used for pathogens inside the human cells
    • Lymphocytes attack and destroy
  • Humoral (antibody-mediated) immunity
    • Use for extracellular pathogens
    • Don’t directly attack pathogens, but tag them for destruction

Adaptive immunity:Antibodies

  • Antibodiesare also called immunoglobulins (Igs)
  • Are composed of four polypeptides linked by disulphidebonds
  • There are 5 classes of antibodies (based on their C regions
    • IgA
      • Found in blood plasma and secretion
      • Prevents pathogens from adhering to epithelia
    • IgD
      • A transmembrane protein on B cells
      • Activation of B cells
    • IgE
      • A transmembrane protein on basophils and mastcells
      • Stimulates the release of histamine (inflammationand allergy)

Figure 21.19

    • IgG
      • Found in blood plasma (andfetus)
      • Important in the secondaryimmune response
    • IgM
      • Found in blood plasma, lymph andtransmembrane of B cells
      • Important in the primary immuneresponse

Adaptive immunity: Lymphocytes

  • T cells and B cells are involved in adaptive immunity, whereas natural killer cells are involved in innateimmunity
  • T cells are produced in the red bone marrow and then migrate to the thymus
    • In the thymus cortex, epithelial cells test if T cells can recognise foreign antigens and antigen-presenting cells
      • If not, they can reshuffle the DNA for their receptors and try a second time
    • In the thymus medulla, macrophages and reticular cells test if T cells react to antigens of one’s ownbody or one’s own antigen-presenting cells
  • B cells maturation occurs in the red bone marrow
    • Also undergo positive and negative selection

Adaptive immunity: Antigen-Presenting Cells

  • Dendritic cells, macrophages, reticular cells and B cells canall function as APCs
  • APC function requires major histocompatibility complex(MHC) proteins
    • Act as identification tags
  • Antigen processing
    • Endocytosis, digest into molecular fragments, displayepitopes in MHC proteins
  • When the T cells detect foreign antigens in the MHCproteins, they initiate an attack (cellular immunity)

Figure 21.19

Cellular immunity

  • Cellular immunity describes T lymphocytes directly attacking diseased or foreign cells
  • Lots of different types of T cells
    • Cytotoxic T cells: perform the attack on pathogens
    • Helper T cells: promote cytotoxic T cells and innate immunity
    • Regulatory T cells: limit the response of other T cells by inhibiting multiplication and cytokinesecretion
    • Memory T cells: responsible for memory, derived from cytotoxic T cells
  • T cell activation
    • Cytotoxic T cell or Helper T cells bind to the MHC protein displaying an epitope
    • T cells have to bind to a second protein on the APC
    • T cells then undergo mitosis to produce a large number of effector cells and memory T cells

Cellular immunity:T cell activation and attack

  • T cell activation
    • Cytotoxic T cell or Helper T cells bind to the MHC proteindisplaying an epitope
    • T cells have to bind to a second protein on the APC
    • T cells then undergo mitosis to produce a large number ofeffector cells and memory T cells
  • Helper T cells attack by secrete interleukins
  • Cytotoxic T cells directly attack and kill other cells by dockingto the cell and delivering a lethal hit of chemicals:
    • Perforin (attack cell membrane) and granzymes (enzymes)
    • Interferons (inhibit viral replication and recruitmacrophages)
    • Tumour necrosis factor (macrophage activation and killscancer cells)
  • Memory T cells are long-lived and require fewer steps to beactivated (speeds up the attack upon re-exposure)

Figure 21.22

Humoral immunity

  • Humoral involves B lymphocytes producing antibodies that bind to antigens to tag them for destructionby other means
    • Less direct than cellular immunity
    • Works in three stages: recognition, attack and memory

Humoral immunity: recognition

Figure 21.25

Humoral immunity: attack

  • Antibodies released by plasma render antigen harmless by:
    • Neutralisation
      • Masking of critical (or pathogenic) regions of the antigen molecule
    • Complement fixation
      • Antibodies bind complement protein to a foreign cell (leads to inflammation, immune clearance,phagocytosis and cytolysis)
    • Agglutination
      • Antibodies clump of enemy cells together, causing immobilisation (which increases theeffectiveness of neutrophils and macrophages)
    • Precipitation
      • Antibodies clump antigen molecules together

Humoral immunity: memory

  • Primary response occurs when firstexposed to an antigen
    • 3-6 days to produce antibodies, butproduces memory B cells as well asplasma cells
  • Secondary response occurs to re-exposure of the antigen
    • Is a rapid response create by memoryB cells
      • The response is so rapid, theantigen has little chance to causeillness

Immune response to implants

  • Both innate and adaptive immune responses occur to any foreign material including medical implants(biomaterial scaffolds, bone implants, medical devices like cochlear implants, LVADs)
    • Surface changes to biomaterial activate the immune system
  • The immune response can lead to
    • Excessive inflammation
    • Impairment of healing
    • Fibrotic encapsulation
    • Tissue destruction
    • Even isolation and rejection of the medical implant
  • The response depends on the interplay between the biomaterial and the host immune system (and thetissue surrounding the implant)
    • Consider surface chemistry (hydrophobicity, moieties, charge) and topography (size, shape, texture)
    • Immune-interactive strategies (immune-isolating coatings, local drug deliver, biomimicry)
